<HEADLINE>
<P>
ENVIRONMENTAL STUDY OKD FOR POSSIBLE FREE ALTERNATIVE TO TOLL ROAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FERNANDO ROMERO and FRANK MESSINA, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The county has authorized an environmental study for what could become a free 
alternative to the planned and as yet unbuilt portion of the Foothill toll road 
between Antonio Parkway and Ortega Highway, county officials said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 At least one county official acknowledged that the environmental impact report 
is partially in response to the potential development of a new community south 
of Rancho Santa Margarita. 
</P>
<P>
 "The county will consider (an alternative road, but) the timing will depend on 
the development proposals for that area by the Santa Margarita Co.," said Harry 
Persaud, chief of transportation planning for the county Environmental 
Management Agency. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our current effort is only addressing the alignment (of the proposed road)," 
Persaud said. He added that his agency is working with the Santa Margarita Co., 
which, as part of the environmental impact report, has been asked to come up 
with a conceptual land-use plan for the Horno planning area. 
</P>
<P>
 The Horno area, a 6,000-acre expanse of rolling hills and grasslands east of 
San Juan Capistrano, has been used during the past 100 years for cattle grazing 
and barley growing. It is near the 5,000-acre Rancho Santa Margarita community, 
also owned by the development company. Company officials anticipate that 40,000 
people will live in the Horno area when development is completed by the turn of 
the century. 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Margarita Co. officials would say only that the alternative road project 
is not their undertaking and that they are only working on the conceptual 
land-use plan. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have always said that we intend to develop the land south of Rancho Santa 
Margarita in a master-planned concept," said company spokeswoman Diane Gaynor. 
</P>
<P>
 But a free road could draw traffic away from the toll road, reducing toll 
revenue. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials for the Transportation Corridor Agencies, which is overseeing the 
tollway construction, said they would not speculate on the matter until the 
county's environmental impact report is completed. 
</P>
<P>
 In any case, said TCA's spokeswoman Lisa Telles, two roads "will obviously be 
needed there eventually." 
</P>
<P>
 In fact, she said, both the Antonio Parkway extension and the unbuilt portion 
of the Foothill corridor are contemplated in the county's Master Plan of 
Arterial Highways, which includes a study of future roads. 
</P>
<P>
 Persaud said that although no firm plans for such an alternative road are 
being considered, the county may build the road if the development plans for 
the Horno area become a reality. 
</P>
</TEXT>
