<HEADLINE>
<P>
PENTECOSTAL FELLOWSHIP TO FORM RACIALLY MIXED ORGANIZATION; RELIGION: COALITION 
WOULD END LONGSTANDING DIVISION. IT WILL INCLUDE PREDOMINANTLY BLACK CHURCH OF 
GOD IN CHRIST AND EXCEED 10 MILLION MEMBERS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN DART, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One of the last national church associations of overwhelmingly white 
denominations, the Pentecostal Fellowship of North America, plans to disband 
and form a more racially mixed body. 
</P>
<P>
 The new umbrella organization for as many as 25 denominations would end a 
longstanding religious division in a group that began, ironically, as an 
interracial movement in Los Angeles in 1906. The proposed fellowship would have 
a constituency exceeding 10 million members, including the largest of them all, 
the predominantly black Church of God in Christ. 
</P>
<P>
 Once on the extreme margins of Christianity because of its humble 
socioeconomic origins and its exuberant beliefs in healing and supernatural 
events, Pentecostalism today boasts of mega-churches and large television 
ministries, as well as its share of controversies. 
</P>
<P>
 The growth has attracted political attention. It was at a national Church of 
God in Christ convention in Memphis, Tenn., on Nov. 14 that President Clinton 
described America's "great crisis of the spirit" in a widely reported 
sermon-speech. 
</P>
<P>
 A task force of 40 white and black church leaders laid plans this month in 
Memphis to reshape the fellowship as early as the next convention in October. 
</P>
<P>
 "Things are moving rapidly with nothing negative in the way," said Pentecostal 
Holiness Bishop B.E. Underwood of Oklahoma City, the fellowship chairman who 
proposed the change. 
</P>
<P>
 Most of the fellowship's 21 denominations have some black members in their 
congregations -- just as the Church of God in Christ has a small minority of 
white members. But black denominational leaders were uninterested in joining 
the fellowship as it is constituted. 
</P>
<P>
 The unusual move to disband gained emotional impetus in October at the 
fellowship's convention in Atlanta when Pastor Jack Hayford of Van Nuys' Church 
on the Way, speaking on behalf of white Pentecostalists to the many black 
churchmen who were convention guests, apologized for "decades of prejudice and 
misunderstanding" and embraced the president of a leading black Pentecostal 
seminary. Hayford also took part in this month's task force meeting. 
</P>
<P>
 "The church historically has reflected or reinforced society's divisions," 
said Hayford, a leader in conservative Christian circles. 
</P>
<P>
 "But it's a happy fact that millions of responsible, repentant, spirit-filled 
believers are . . . seeking a full recovery from the crippling impact and 
spiritual embarrassment of that past divisiveness," Hayford wrote in a Jan. 16 
bulletin for his church's 8,000 members. 
</P>
<P>
 The new fellowship, like the one scheduled for dismantling, would be a 
volunteer association of like-minded believers that has no authority over 
member denominations. 
</P>
<P>
 But the opportunity to "rub shoulders and talk" with culturally conservative 
white denominations such as the 2.2-million-member Assemblies of God will 
"automatically make everyone concerned about social issues," Bishop Gilbert 
Patterson of Memphis said. 
</P>
<P>
 "As we face the 21st Century, I believe the impossible task of bringing blacks 
and whites together is about to take place," said the Church of God in Christ 
bishop who will host the October meeting. 
</P>
<P>
 Pentecostalism as a full-fledged movement began in Los Angeles with the 
1906-09 Azusa Street Mission as a racially mixed revival by a black preacher, 
the Rev. William Seymour. 
</P>
<P>
 After a black-white split in 1914, denominations developed along racial lines 
and mostly in rural and poor urban locales. The Pentecostal Fellowship of North 
America was formed in 1948 but black churches were not invited to join. 
</P>
<P>
 Pentecostalism has been shunned by many mainstream churches that claimed that 
speaking in unknown tongues and other claims related to being "filled with the 
Holy Spirit" created divisions among Christians. The most animated churches 
were often derisively called "holy rollers." Foursquare Gospel churches begun 
in the 1920s were linked for decades with its flamboyant founder, evangelist 
Aimee Semple McPherson of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Whether the congregations were black or white, Pentecostal churches were 
largely in rural and economically depressed urban locales and their clergy 
poorly educated. Things began to change in the 1960s when groups of Pentecostal 
believers surfaced within mainline Protestant and Roman Catholic churches. They 
and many independent congregations with Pentecostal beliefs described 
themselves as charismatic, derived from the Greek word for divine gifts. 
</P>
<P>
 Today, the theological borders between Pentecostal/charismatic churches and 
their old antagonists, evangelical churches, have frequently become blurred as 
both sides focused more on common beliefs and their mutual opposition to 
abortion, pornography and gay and lesbian rights. 
</P>
<P>
 Pentecostal/charismatic ranks include scandal-stained televangelists Jim 
Bakker and Jimmy Swaggart as well as religious television network chiefs Pat 
Robertson in Virginia Beach, Va., and Paul Crouch in Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 Pentecostalism also includes well-regarded clergy such as Los Angeles Bishop 
Charles Blake, who serves as pastor of the nearly 11,000-member West Angeles 
Church of God in Christ. 
</P>
<P>
 Blake was cautiously optimistic about the pending change in the Pentecostal 
Fellowship. 
</P>
<P>
 "Because black churches are primarily in urban centers and white churches are 
mostly in the suburbs it will not be easy for us to have intense 
collaboration," Blake said. "But breaking down the walls is altogether 
necessary and I support any sign of reconciliation." 
</P>
<P>
 Blake praised the work of Hayford in facilitating fellowship locally between 
black and white pastors of various denominations, primarily through the "Love 
L.A." prayer meetings held since 1987 at Hollywood Presbyterian Church and, on 
major occasions, at the Crenshaw Christian Center in South-Central Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Hayford said after the task force meeting last week that nothing else has a 
higher priority for him than bringing about a new fellowship. 
</P>
<P>
 Patterson of the Church of God in Christ said he keeps on his office wall a 
copy of a Los Angeles Times article that ran April 18, 1906, headlined "Weird 
Babel of Tongues, New Set of Fanatics Is Breaking Loose." The article, widely 
reproduced in Pentecostal circles, described in colorful language the preaching 
of the one-eyed William Seymour and the zeal of the racially mixed 
congregation. 
</P>
<P>
 The Church of God in Christ was formed in 1907 after the Rev. C. H. Mason and 
two brethren visited the modest mission, which stood on the edge of what is now 
Little Tokyo in Los Angeles. Returning to Memphis, Mason ordained many white 
ministers in later years, but a major group of white preachers broke off in 
1914 to form the Assemblies of God. 
</P>
<P>
 "The racial barriers that were rebuilt within a decade were understandable 
given the culture then," Hayford said. "But (the original mission) was 
nonetheless a vision of what might have been all these years." 
</P>
</TEXT>
