<HEADLINE>
<P>
PACKARD BELL EMPLOYEES GIVEN 2 WEEKS TO DECIDE ON LAYOFFS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By H. G. REZA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 About 420 Packard Bell employees still reeling from Monday's earthquake 
received another jolt Friday when company officials told them they would be 
laid off in two weeks -- unless they accepted an earlier offer to take a pay 
cut of up to 30% and move to Utah. 
</P>
<P>
 John Hlavac, the Packard Bell vice president who signed the termination 
notices, declined to say how many employees refused to relocate and were being 
laid off. The termination notices blamed the sudden layoffs on quake damage 
suffered by the personal computer manufacturer's service center facility in 
Chatsworth, which fields phone calls from customers. 
</P>
<P>
 "It couldn't have come at a worse time for many of us," said Greg Black, 39, a 
one-year Packard Bell employee. "I mean, right in the middle of all that is 
happening to us already." 
</P>
<P>
 The company also has plans to move its 1,100-employee headquarters out of 
Chatsworth. 
</P>
<P>
 "They told us we would have to take pay cuts because the cost of living is 
lower in Utah. But it's just wage busting," said Black, who lives in Chatsworth 
with his wife and two young children. "My cut would be almost 25%, but some 
people are losing 30% in pay." 
</P>
<P>
 Service center employees received a letter from Hlavac dated Jan. 10 that said 
the pay cuts are justified because of "a lower cost of living in Utah, lower 
sales taxes in Utah and reduced state income taxes."  
</P>
<P>
 The letter promised bonuses of $75 a week until their termination for 
employees who chose not to relocate. Many expected to continue working until 
March. Instead, the workers got two weeks' notice Friday. 
</P>
<P>
 Jonathan Blake, 44, said he was told he would have to take a pay cut from 
$11.18 an hour to $8.50 an hour if he moved to Utah. 
</P>
<P>
 Since the quake, the Canoga Park man has been living with his wife and two 
children in a tent outside their damaged home. When Blake was notified of his 
impending layoff, his wife was at home, awaiting the arrival of a city building 
inspector who was to decide if the house was habitable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
